:1592"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "CYP26A1, B1 and C1", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9861544966697693, "span": {"begin": 894, "end": 912}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:26536"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Retinoic Acid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9980379343032837, "span": {"begin": 968, "end": 981}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:10966"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Retinoic Acid Receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9946687817573547, "span": {"begin": 968, "end": 991}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5917"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "RARs", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9901714324951172, "span": {"begin": 993, "end": 997}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:4913"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Retinoid", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9884074330329895, "span": {"begin": 1003, "end": 1011}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6256"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Retinoid X Receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9982210993766785, "span": {"begin": 1003, "end": 1023}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6256"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "RXRs", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9903275966644287, "span": {"begin": 1025, "end": 1029}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "target genes", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.909494161605835, "span": {"begin": 1067, "end": 1079}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:1592"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "Cyp26 family", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9707767963409424, "span": {"begin": 1240, "end": 1252}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "target cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8941227197647095, "span": {"begin": 1316, "end": 1328}}, {"id": ["mim:612376", "mesh:D015473"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "acute promyelocytic leukemia", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999973773956299, "span": {"begin": 1396, "end": 1424}}, {"id": ["mesh:D000152"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "cystic acne", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999982118606567, "span": {"begin": 1429, "end": 1440}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "target cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.8681299686431885, "span": {"begin": 1504, "end": 1516}}], "text": "Retinoic acid (RA) function and metabolism   RA and retinoid signaling is central for numerous physiological processes, and has important roles within reproduction, vision, development and the immune system (O&#39;Byrne &amp; Blaner, 2013). As an important morphogen, the levels of RA is tightly controlled within tissues both spatially and temporally. Both insufficient and excess RA has proven to cause severe adverse effects (Kedishvili, 2013).  RA homeostasis is maintained by tissue-specific enzymes controlling a 2-step biosynthesis pathway: the precursor retinol is converted into retinaldehyde via retinol dehydrogenases (RDHs). Retinaldehyde dehydrogenases (RALDHs) then irreversibly oxidize retinaldehyde into biologically active RA (reviewed by (Shannon et al, 2017)). RA is removed via degradation to polar inactive metabolites by cytochrome P450 (CYP) family hydroxylases; chiefly CYP26A1, B1 and C1 (Topletz et al, 2015).  RA signals through the nuclear Retinoic Acid Receptors (RARs) and Retinoid X Receptors (RXRs) thereby regulating transcription of target genes (Cunningham &amp; Duester, 2015).  &nbsp;  Ectopic RA as Key Event  Inhibition or disruption of any of the enzymes in the RA degradation pathway, including the Cyp26 family, lead to increased concentrations of biologically active RA in target cells.  Equally, application of RA for medical treatments, including for acute promyelocytic leukemia and cystic acne, lead to increased concentrations of biologically active RA in target cells.", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:52:49 +0000 2026"}